annotation: Black looks to get his pieces out quickly.
"Putting the question."
Breaking the pin.
Sacrificing three Pawns for a Black Knight.
It appears that 8...PxP will win White's QR. But White thinks he has a refutation.
Black goes ahead with his plan.
White's secret weapon. Now he can play 10 QxP and save his QR -- he thinks.
Brilliant! Now White's Queen is pinned ant cannot capture the Pawn.
Practically forced as he must break the pin.
Guards the Pawn.
Forced. But now...
White's QR is still trapped. Rusakov resigns.
i hate the Sicilian so whenever i reach this point i see an opportunity to go straight into the middle game by exchanging the knights!!
with this move  i have completely turned the game from a potentially complected Sicilian opening to  a straight forward open middle game with lots of tension in the center which are my specialty!!
busts up the center! and black is not prepared!!
i remove blacks only active piece therefore i gain control of the center and do whatever i please at the cost of a pawn!!
i think this was a mistake by black pawn takes looks better!!
black's pieces are completely useless!!
blunder!! bishop c8 looks better!!
black is afraid of trading the bishop his only piece that was actually active in this game but i don't think he has a choice either way i win quite comfortably!
finally black get a another piece to work with so he thinks but i stopped that thought in its track on my next move!!
game set and match!!
black finally agreed with me and resigned!!

Closed Catalan
Alternative variation: 6... c6 [ is a more common way to keep the position closed. The game could continue] 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. b3 [with the option of 8...b6 or 8...b5 here.]
Alternative variation: 6... dxc4 [ is the strongest move because White will need to eventually take time to recapture the pawn.] 7. Qc2 a6 8. Qxc4 b5 $11

Not the most accurate move.
Alternative variation: 7. Nc3 Bb7 8. Ne5 Na6 9. b3 [ gives White a very nice position with a slight edge.]
Alternative variation: 7... c5 [ seems to be the best way to take advantage of 7.Qc2. Black should now try to get his rook on the c-file.] 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Rd1 Bb7 [with an even game.]
Alternative variation: 8. cxd5 [keeps the edge for White.] Nxd5 9. Nc3 $14
Alternative variation: 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 Ng4 $15 [and White is having trouble defending the e5 pawn.]
Alternative variation: 9... Nxd5 [uses a nice tactic to defend against Ne5-c6.] 10. Nc6 Nb4 11. Nxb4 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Bxb4 $11
Good move. Taking advantage of the hole on c6.
Alternative variation: 10... Bxc6 11. Qxc6 [ isn't any better for Black. The pawns on d5 and c7 are too weak to hold onto.]

Black has the opportunity to take a large lead in development here by harrassing White's queen.
Alternative variation: 13. Nc3 [ developing and protecting e5. If] Bxe2 14. Re1 [wins the bishop.]
Alternative variation: 13... Rfc8 14. Qf4 Ne4 [followed by Ne7-f6.]
Alternative variation: 15... Qxa3 [only move.] 16. Nxa3 Rac8 [and White should be able to win in this position being up a pawn and having the bishop pair.]

Game Summary: In the opening White made a small inaccuracy with 7.Qc2. Black had a chance to equalize at that point by playing 7...c5 and grabbing space in the center. After 8.Ne5 Black could have weakened White's pawn structure with 8...Nxe5 also taking the initiative. White played a very strong game after that point taking advantage of a small mistake by black (9...exd5) and converting his edge to a win.
Petrosian's move of choice. His style looks similar to Botvinnik but unlike his great predecessor Petrosian had a very deep tactical vision.
Black wants to play a Semi-Slav or the very Sharp Botvinnik variation.
White develops his Queen early which is not uncommon in the QGD. This square is particularly useful is you plan on exchanging on d5 and preventing an early Bishop sortie to f5.

Black wants to resolve the pin. This is usually a good move since in some lines there are some tactics on h7 winning that pawn. There is a small downside however in case White plays the exchange variation and castles long the h-pawn might speed up White's pawn storm on the K-side. There are many subtleties like this in the QGD and it's very difficult to spot them if you don't have enough experience with the opening. Memorizing lines isn't enough.

The most elastic move. White doesn't want to hand over the Bishop pair so early on in the game and he doesn't want to retreat to h4 which would make Black's task of equalizing easier since he would enter normal positions of the Orthodox Defense where White's Queen isn't optimally placed on c2.

A very normal move and it's very hard to find anything else for Black. The problem is that once this Knight has developed White can take with much more confidence on d5 since taking with the e-pawn leads to normal positions where White can choose between the minority attack and castling long while taking with the c-pawn is inferior because the Bc8 is still a problem and c6 isn't available for the Knight.
Waiting no more White exchanges on d5. The exchange variation of the QGD is a very dangerous weapon especially in the hands of a strategist like Petrosian.

Unzicker was fearful of normal structures that would have resulted after recapturing with the e-pawn after which the Qc2 and the Bf4 make perfect sense so he recaptures with the c-pawn. White is unable to play the minority attack nor is castling long a good alternative. The problem is that Black doesn't have a good plan himself in this structure. Let's examine the other two possible recaptures. Taking with the e-pawn can lead to the following sequence of moves 9...exd5 10. h3 (preserving the Bf4 and preparing the pawn storm) Re8 (the standard plan for Black who doesn't have many squares to shuffles pieces around) 11. Bd3 (one of the reasons why The Exchange variation is good for White is that his pieces develop on optimal squares) Nf8 (making room for the Bc8 to come into play) 12. 0-0-0 (burning all bridges but thanks to Black's 7th White can be optimist he'll crash through first). I guess this was the position Black wanted to avoid in recapturing with the c-pawn. But there is another recapture possible with the Knight. After 9...Nxd5 10. Nxd5! exd5 11. Bd3 White can play his second plan the minority attack which is very hard to meet and the missing pair of Knights favor White because Black has fewer attacking chances.
Normal development. White's plan in this position is to use the c-file for infiltration and reduce Black's counterplay to zero.

A strategical error. Never move pawns on the flank where you are weaker and this game proves it tenfold. The reason behind this statement is that any pawn moves create weaknesses and your opponent will have something to target. However it's very difficult to find a working plan for Black Unzicker must have been wanted to prevent Nb5 and try to resolve his Bc8 somehow.

White is in no hurry Black can't contest the c-file any time soon. 11. h3 would have been an alternative but Petrosian must have not been afraid of losing the Bishop pair and wasn't in a hurry to weaken his castled position.

Would you believe that after this move Black is lost? He has just created permanent weak spots on the c-file while giving his opponent a target in the b-pawn. The only sensible looking alternative was 11...Nh5 but even after that White has the strong reply 12. Be5! Nxe5 (12...f6 fails to 13. Nxd5! fxe5 (13...exd5 loses after 14. Bh7+ Kh8 15. Bc7 Qe8 16. Bg6 Rf7 17. Bxh5 and White has won the piece back and will soon win the exchange as well) 14. Nc7 exd4 15. Nxd4 Ne5 16. Bh7+ Kh8 17. Nxa8 these tactical variations show the hidden dangers in Black's cramped position) 13. dxe5 and Black has two bad pieces the Bc8 and the Nh5.
Very impetuously played by Petrosian. He takes advantage of the pin on the a-file and force Black to further advance his pawns.
Forced or else Black loses a pawn. He can't afford to open the a-file because the a-pawn will be very weak and cannot stand for long.
Stronger than 13. Ne2 this Knight is heading towards b3.

Perhaps not the most active plan of defense mainly because White could have played 14. a5! and the pawn is immune because of Qc8. But both these players had already formulated the plans after which they would arrange their pieces and were staying on-course.
Consistent to the previous move.
Black secures the pawn structure on the Q-side and prepares to exchange a pair of Bishops.
Petrosian was a great admirer of Nimzovitch and was no doubt pleased to have setup an early blockade against the Q-side pawns.
Black solves his bad piece but in the process has created further more insolvable problems.
This should be a good lesson if your opponent has weaknesses don't be shy to exchange pieces. In the endgame weak pawns fall much faster than in middlegames.
Using the undefended position of the Ra6 to secure the c-file.
Heading for either c4 or e4.

No qualms over the superiority of Bishops over Knights. In structures like these where there is only one open file on the board the center in locked and you control that file Knights are much better than Bishops.
Petrosian wants to double the Rooks with tempo.
Forcing White to retreat the intruder but Black has wasted a tempo here. More sensible was 20...Nb6.
The Knight wasn't doing anything on b8.

White has doubled Rooks and now must start attacking. Generally if your only advantage is an open file then that won't be enough to secure victory. Your opponent will either find a way to exchange Rooks and simply defend everything. So from a strategic viewpoint once you have an open file it's time to create new targets of attack or at least provoke your opponent into creating weaknesses that he can't defend. Look at this position. White stands better but he isn't winning. There are no concrete targets to attack. Black has a small space advantage on the Q-side which is enough for him to regroup his pieces and defend albeit passively. White has to use the dominance on the c-file in other ways.
Aiming for c4 and attacking a4. Since controlling the c4 square with a pawn is possible only by removing the blockading Nb3 White contests it with a piece.
Since Black doesn't have his LSB anymore the light squares are the perfect point to infiltrate on the Q-side.
This Knight wasn't very active on f3 so White exchanges it off.

Retreating would have meant loss of all prospects for this Knight so Unzicker rightly swaps it off. Sometimes it's better to exchange pieces even if your position is worse than retreating that piece to a passive square.
Since Black can't contest the c-file this is a safe recapture.

Black's alternative defense plan would be to exchange Queens and go for a passive defense while allowing White his supremacy on the c-file. This might have put a more stubborn resistance but very few players like passive positions.
White can't win anything on the Q-side. Black can defend everything and he's not going to run out of moves. So it's time to change the plan.

First placing all the K-side pawns on the same color as his opponent's Bishop. This is an important point in endgames where many beginners place their pawns on opposite color squares so that the pawns will be safe from capture. This is a mistake with one notable exception opposite color Bishop endings because you want to use your pawns to restrict the Bishop's movement. Petrosian knew this and moved his pawns accordingly.
Unzicker knew this as well and move his pawns to the opposite color squares as his Bishop so that the pawns will control the light squares and his Bishop the dark ones.

Preparing for a brave plan. White has seen that things have stalled on the Q-side and that action is needed elsewhere. So he rightfully judged that he can move his King to the Q-side where it will be perfectly safe and start attacking on the K-side. Black doesn't have that option since his King wouldn't make it past the c-file. A brilliant concept by Petrosian and something to remember in case you run out of ideas.

Not that Black can't start active plans because Petrosian has placed all his pieces on optimal squares to prevent this. All he can do is sit and watch the march of the White King knowing undoubtedly what is coming next.
Time to start attacking the K-side.
Black needs to activate his pieces before it's too late.
Preparing to swing the Rook to the other side of the board.
Offering a Queen swap that Black dare not accept. This is another advantage to having the King on the Q-side he can act as a blockader to Black's pawns in case an endgame is reached.

Forced after 38...Qxb5 39. axb5 a4 40. b6 Rad7 41. Nc5 Bxc5 42. dxc5 the endgame is won particularly because White can hold off the passed pawns with his King. Here is an instructive sequence: 42...b3 trying to limit the White King 43. Rd1 with the notion of coming to d4 and b4 and also making room for the King 43...e5 stopping one idea 44. Kc1 but not the other and the King marches to b4 and wins the Black pawns.
Gaining space on the K-side.
Black has to stay passive trying to blockade the pawns with 39...f5 fails to 40. Rb6 Kh6 41. Rcc6 Bc7 42. Ra6 Rxa6 43. Rxa6 Qb8 44. Nc5 and Black's Q-side crumbles

Probably the sealed move. Back in those days games were adjourned at move 40 and play would continue the next day. This also explains why Petrosian didn't hurry before with his plan he wanted to analyze at home before playing it on the board.
Black is forced to open the lines around his King.

I'd like to take this moment to commend Unzicker's defensive play. Many modern Grandmasters would have lost their temper by now and blundered away their position. But in those days defending was an art alongside attacking. Modern Grandmasters have lost the capability to defend positions like this they don't like to suffer in passivity and would rather risk an unsound counterplay than submit to shuffling their pieces around.
The second assault on the Black King.
Good defensive move Black intends to exchange Queens with Qf5+ or Qxg6+ in case White exchanges pawns.
The King is now secure and attack can continue.
Removing the King from the dangerous h-file.
White has no intentions of swapping Queens. This retreats with tempo hitting the Rd8.
Black brings another piece into the defense of his bare King.
Threatening Rg1. Black's pieces don't coordinate well and his King is still very exposed.
Trying to find a secure refuge out of the two open lines on the K-side.

A slight inaccuracy 48. Qh2 would have been more forceful. It's very instructive that because of the weak King Black can't defend the Q-side properly for example 48. Qh2 Ke8 49. Rc7 Rxc7 50. Rxc7 Ra8 (defending a5) 51. Qe2! Kf8 52. Qb5 Bd8 53. Rc1! Be7 (forced or else Qb7 winning the Rook) 54. Qb7 Re8 55. Rh1! (taking another poke at the Black King) Bf6 (making room and defending h8) 56. Nxa5 Qg2 57. Qxb4+ Kg7 58. Rc1 and White is two pawns up.
With the idea of b3+.
Repeating the position but there is no other way of defending a5.
White finally breaks through. See my commentary on move 48.
Black chose another defense. It's still insufficient. Petrosian plays very accurately and gives no more second chances.
51...Ra8 doesn't work either after 52. R8c7 Bg7 53. Nc5 Qh6 54. Qg2 Rd6 55. Rh1 Qf6 56. Nd7+ Rxd7 57. Rxd7 and with an exchange up and very active pieces Black can't last much longer.
The Knight finally comes to the c5 square and what a great moment for it.
A spite check but a harmless one.
A double attack the Rd6 isn't defended the Rd8 is pinned.
Black resigned. After 55...Qxf5 56. Nd7+ wins a full Rook. A remarkable game by Petrosian.
Philidor's Defense -- except that Philidor was not yet playing competitive chess. Maybe the great Frenchman was observing and learning what NOT to do?
As White especially when your opponent chooses a defense that restricts his own space you must always attack.
Black counterattacks with verve. But perhaps a Knight move was in order first?
This move is definitely weakening. Now de Legal finishes his opponent in style.
A spectacular move. If Black declines the sacrifice with 5...PxN 6 QxB wins a Pawn and gives White three active pieces to zero for Black. If he accepts...
...which he does...
...mate is forced.

Known as de Legal's trap this combination has been used by masters for centuries to take down duffers in simultaneous exhibitions. It has even appeared in modified form in some games between two masters!
It's a very common and very easy to be developed through so many variations. Play as white I usually start with 1. e2 e4 and hope black doesn't perform Sicilian Defense I hate that ...
A common and a quite good response to 1. e2 e4 ...
Initiating an attack to black's pawn I move the knight to f3... (King's Knight Opening C40)
Black move his pawn to d6 starting a strong Philidor's Defence but here come a new problem. It's very hard to develop his king's bishop...
Actually an usual response to break Philidor's Defence is moving white pawn to d4 but I want to try something new: moving queen's knight to c3.

3. ....... Bg4?
I don't know why black move the bishop to g4 it's very weak... Actually Nc6 is better..
But as long it doesn't threat my king I let it stand here.
I move my bishop to c4 to prepare castling a very common idea for beginner like me.
Black move his pawn to h6 maybe he want to stop my knight's movements. Here I see a very good chance to attack black... A queen sacrifice!

5. Nxe5!?
I think it's the most interesting move in this game. Giving my queen to black!

Actually black must think it deeply because I won't give my queen without any reasons. But maybe he thought that I make an error or because I am still beginner (the last is right!)

ANALYSIS=
How if black refuse my queen and take my knight at e5? There's no problem. I'll take the g4 bishop and performing a well developed position.

My bishop do a starting check 6. Bxf7+ !! 
The king has no choices. He just can move to e7 since d7 is guarded by my knight.
And a very beautiful checkmate that can't be avoided since 5. ..... Bxd1 ??
The French Defense which can leave Black with good prospects if played well or a horribly cramped game if as in this case it is played badly.
Giving up the center too easily.
I prefer a developmental system of B-K2 N-KB3 and O-O for Black in this position. Followed up by N-Q2 so as to recapture on KB3 with a Knight this system keeps Black's King safe.
Weakening. The natural spot for the N is KB3 especially if K-side castling is in the works. it provides much better defense from KB3.
White exploits the weakend Black K-side with a pin.
If Black's B were on K2 and his N on KB3 this move would be acceptable. Instead White rips away Black's flimsy defenses.
If Black tries 7... K-R1 here 8 Q-R5! is a deadly stroke. Note that if Black's N were at KB3 White would have to exchange off his own N to get ...Q-R5 in.
The King-hunt begins. Black is in dire straits.
Black prepares to guard 9 Q-N4 ch with 9...N-N3. But...
There is no defense. Mate is now forced.
As is so often the case this move is deadly.
A beautiful attack forced through elegantly by White.
My attempt to seal the king side has failed!
Further breach of my King side.
Here 28...Ra5 looses out to 29 a4...

Never go grabbing other's pawns when my own f7 is threatened.
Better 32...Rhf8 first.
Start of a very nice combination that I did not spot...
Only hope is to get to the back rank...
While the attack looks threatening there is no immediate checkmate.

This is a white blunder. While h3 solves the immediate checkmate problem for white this move enables a draw position to become available to black.
Better 37 Rdc7! which removes blacks checkmate threat and retains pressure on black king.

The draw is a reality.
39 g3 is met with ...Rf2
40 Kg1 Qxg3
41 Kh1 Qg2 ++
this move does not even exist in the opening database... moving the bishop twice doesn't feel right; i don't really see the point in this move
asking the question
cool for me 2 bishops
developing with threat is always good... lsb does no longer exist to exploit the diagonal
again developing with threat the pawn on e4 is my obvious target
finish development
e5 fails for queen exd5 gives chance of exd5 followed by d4 with the discovered queen attack; e4 looms anyway...
preventing material loss with d4
claiming even more space with threat
and again not only claiming space but driving away the knight from defense of the weak e4-pawn
defending the pawn with the cost of the second bishop
now i have 2 bishops and a good space advantage a passed pawn everythings looks great
forcing the second knight to retreat
the idea here is to put further pressure on e4 if the knight on d4 has to move there is a possible material win
over-defending e4
the e5-pawn is very important for me to keep space so i thought its a good idea to give some protection
ok the threat here is knight h5 or f5 which could force an exchange with the loss of my bishop which i did not like at this point
the knight can still access h5 or f5 but my dsb can retreat to g7 or even h8 and keep support for e5 and ultimately the h8-a1 diagonal
propably eying on the b7 bishop a pawn push at this point i do not care
denying g5 and f5 to the knight and therefore prventing expansion

defends e4
e5 is well protected and g5 is useless at this point so i don't care
gains space and stops possible h2-push
this is the first sign of lackings space so there is no real counter play
a perfect position the bishop can hardly become stronger

waiting for a strike... my only chess book says: there is no need to hurry if you have space just squeeze to death: my plan here is to gain more space and enhance the minor pieces; my bishop is clearly superior to the knights... in my opinion white has to sacrifice some material here to do not get crushed
the idea is to make place for the bishop because queen an rook are on diagonal and after Ba6 c3 is a serious threat
even if the rook is not there any more the position for the bishop is perfect
c2 seems to be the week point so the bishop tries to penetrate deeper into the position
ok now this opened the b-file and gives some activity to the white rook but i hardly see any counter-play but the c2-pawn is a big target right now
like a tank in a forest...

(plan here was to push the d-pawn)
try to keep the fat lady enclosed no way out and Bb5 is a threat
pressuring c2 again...

with lack of space exchanging theoretically favors the enclosed in player but here this exchange removes the most active white piece
defending against Bb5
Rook is strong on the 7th rank

till now no material is lost :)

this ends the ride the game was resigned here
Nothing special here. e4: the most common opening for white.

Petrov's defense. Not too many people understand this opening but I have used it on several occasions and see scenarios where it works and situations where it doesn't. One thing I am confused do most games end up in a draw with this opening or is there an advantage to one color and why?
? - Not the response I was expecting. It traps the bishop and seems to hinder development just to protect the center e4 pawn.

My general response to the protection of e4. In this case my c8 bishop is free to roam and attack or defend white. I know black bishop is cut off but I usually don't mind this as the game usually develops into a situation in which this bishop becomes very useful.
?! - Seems like a move late but still serves the purpose of attacking the center. Seems this would be more powerful at 3. d4!?

Simple. I am just doing textbook strategy. The white bishop is still not developed so it seems as if I am ahead. Wonder if I castle too early or is the main goal here to get the king into a protected position by castling this early? Any feedback here would be appreciated.
Blocks 5. ... Bg4 but development of the c2-bishop is still quite bad.
? - Is it just a manner of trading off the knights or is this person looking at something else?

Because I don't want to trade here right away. I want white to play aggressively. It benefits me. I can set up successful counters without much retribution from white. (Even though I do block in my queen.)
? - Transposing to a three pawn attack? Break my chain? Not exactly what I expected white to do although it is a pretty aggressive approach. Let's see where it leads...
! - Took my chance to play aggressive since I see myself winning this exchange and taking advantage of the under-developed position white is in.
White is fighting to hold the center. But I don't think there is enough here for white to hold on to. Being the strategist here I let white decide which combinations he will approach me with.
?? - I seriously think the bishop was a better option. Or better yet why trade when down a pawn? Perhaps Nbd2(?) was a better option? Or even Be2 giving white king a protection route to castle.
! - Confirming my grasp on the central position. Both bishop is protected and pawn can't be taken. Removing the knights really opened the board which can be good or bad for black.

?? - FATAL miscalculation. Perhaps thinking of queen-side castle to try and regain central position? White is way too open to even think of trying this. 11. Bd3 to allow the king to reenter a closed protected area by castling kingside. This BAD miscalculation costs black dearly.
My opponent in this game kneilca sent me a challenge with the message "Please feel free to comment on the game" so after a long gap I have another annotation to share with everyone.

Two Knights Defence always my favourite response to Bc4 and an opening I've been playing a lot recently thanks to Freddy's mini-tournament on the Traxler variation (4. Ng5 Bc5). Good fun but for this game I decided to go back to the more mainstream 4... d5. As Ion said in a comment on someone's annotation the great thing about the Two Knights is that all the variations can lead to exciting play :)
White's most enterprising continuation violating the prohibition on moving the same piece twice but with a strong attack on f7. Black must decide how to meet this attack...
...and the most common response is this pawn sacrifice hoping to gain an advantage in development in compensation.

White is forced to block his attack on f7 since 5. Bxd5? Nxd5 6. exd5 Qxg5 7. bxc6 Qxg2 is clearly advantageous for Black. However White is attacking Black's knight and the "obvious" 5... Nxd5 is not really recommended (6. d4! is great for White). Most common is 5... Na5 but it's not the only possibility...

...since Black also has this option my favourite. So far I have a 100% win record in games with this line; partly because the move considered White's best response 6. Bf1 is simply never found at the board by players who haven't seen it before. The point of this bizarre retreat is to guard g2 and to preserve the bishop from exchange (either 6. Be2 or 6. Bb3 is met by Nd4); and Black still has to deal with the threat to his knight. Since both 6... Nxd5 7. Bxb5 and 6... Qxd5 7. Nc3 are fine for White Black normally plays 6... Nd4 transposing into the labyrinthine Fritz variation.

Getting back to the actual game: Black has only one realistic response to this move 6... Qxd5 putting g2 under fire. In this line Black hopes his pressure on White's kingside will be sufficient compensation for the pawn.
This is the most common move here; White hopes to weather the storm. 7. Bf1 is now too passive and usually leads to Black victory in past games in the database.

Castling in this position is very bold; maybe too bold. The main alternative is 8. Qf3 hoping to defuse Black's pressure. Of course Black would not exchange but would play 8... e4; however the long diagonal would at least then be blocked.

Black threatens immediate mate and now 9. Qf3 is less attractive since the pawn on e4 will be well supported and will cut off the g5 knight's retreat. 9. Nf3 is a possibility but the pawn move played in the game is in fact the most common.
This move and White's response are automatic.
Black now "kicks" the knight hoping to start a kingside pawn storm. Getting a pawn to g4 would be especially good since White cannot capture without allowing Qxg2 checkmate.

Since Black intends to storm with the kingside pawns he naturally castles on the other wing; the h8 rook can support the pawns from its home square while the a8 rook needs to be brought into the action.

White opens a line for the bishop and also defends the e4 square to discourage Black from trying to annoy the crucial f3 pawn. It looks as though this defence is ineffective the d-pawn being pinned against the queen but in one game in the database Black unwisely tried 12... e4 and regretted it after 13. fxe4 Nxe4 14. Qg4+.
White completes development so more pieces are available to defend the kingside; a sensible decision.

The knight makes way for the f-pawn to advance and also defends the g-pawn so the h-pawn can advance. This looks dangerous; though perhaps Black is playing a little overconfidently and striking immediately with ...g4 was more to the point.

(?) Not sure about this move. White clearly can't aim to counter Black's pawn storm with one of his own as his pawns are too far behind. Instead I suspect the intention was 17. b4 Bb6 18. b5 to kick Black's queen off the long diagonal. A nice idea but too slow; Black just responds Qg6 and Grond crawls on. What can be recommended instead? Perhaps 16. Ne2 getting another defender to the kingside and creating the possibility of blocking one of Black's lines by d4.

White's slowness gives Black the confidence to (finally!) play this move. Now the enemy are at the gates and the Rohirrim are nowhere in sight. The immediate threat is 17... gxf3 18. gxf3 Qxf3+ 19. Qxf3 Bxf3#; White could instead play 18. g3 but then the knight is frozen in place and Black can easily break open White's kingside by advancing the f- and h-pawns. The only way to defend f3 (remember it can't move) is to move the f2 knight; but it has no squares. 17. Nh3 gxh3 also undermines g2 and leads to checkmate while 17. Nxg4 fxg4? 18. Ne4 would dampen Black's attack but instead 17... Rxg4 and White can't take the rook.
White capitulates rapidly after this move overlooking that the pawn was defended but by now it hardly matters.
Otherwise Black plays 18... g3 19. h3 gxf2 cutting White's communications so that there's no good defence to the threat of Qg6 and Qxg2#. But against the move played Black has:
A "removal of the guard" tactic. The obvious materialistic recapture is not in this case to be condemned; Black would have a similar follow-up to any move by White now.

White resigned citing the forced line 21... Bxf3+ 22. Qxf3 Qxf3+ 23. Rg2 Qxg2#. Thank you for the game and thank you for giving me the opportunity to talk about one of my favourite opening variations :)
Already Doubrava is overcautious.
Dadian by contrast plays aggressive chess.
Way too conservative. Also blocks the QB.
Dadian develops quickly and efficiently.

White is sacing the Queen just to drag out the Black King to the middle of the board. 4... e5 is a mistake in this opening.

This Bishop is needed to drive pieces away from the hole at d5.
5...Be6 was what the doctor ordered!
Queen needed to move here on move 5 in order to prevent the Bishop going to c4.
Although this simple developing move prevents the Maroczy Bind (c4 preventing d5) Black's grip of the d5 square was lost long ago.
White should play a3 incase of Na5 preserving his Bishop for the a2-g8 diagonal. Removing a potential defender of the d5 square is not a bad idea though.

This highlights the inaccuracy of White's last move. If he was to move his dark squared Bishop he should have moved it to e3 in anticipation of this move. White has no control over whether he keeps his King's Bishop. In this position Black needs to take b3 and then retreat his Bishop to c6 via d7.
A waste of time which forces the issue. Here White should play Bxf6.
Although this cripples White's Kingside Pawns after the exchanges Black will not have sufficient means to attack the scattered Pawns; this cannot compensate for the "chasm" on d5.
Black squanders his last chance to preserve a defender for the crucial d5 square.
White fears the Bishop using f4 or h4 as an outpost and the weakness of the f Pawns.

A waiting move? Is Black intending to play f5? The Black King feels safer on this square but where is the threat from White? Black desperately needed to take the Bishop which is lucky to still be on the board. In going all out for his stategy of fixing d5 as a weakness White's development has been slow and inaccurate. Black on the other hand despite dreaming of winning the f3 Pawn cannot drive the King away from guard duty at the same time as threatening the Pawn. Here Black may have played for a draw by three-fold repitition with Qg5-f4-g5-f4 etc.
The move we've all been waiting for; the Bishop goes to its best square at the first opportunity.
Weakening the light squares on the Queenside making the Bishop more powerful than either of Black's Rooks.
White forces Black to defend passively in order to complete his development.
Playing into White's hands who albeit rather slowly is at least able to transfer his Rooks to the Queenside.
Another King move?
Black eyes the f2 Pawn as a target.
A multi-purpose move. White intends to fix Blacks Pawns for the mobility of his own pieces. The d8 Rook is en prise; White can use his Queenside Pawn majority to secure a passed Pawn.

A risky move. White cannot attack the h4 Pawn so it needs no defence; Blacks Pawn structure enables the Bishop to have the freedom of the whole board! Has there ever been a more powerful Bishop in the History of Chess?
Preparing to throw Pwans forward.
A blunder! Poor Black is targeting f2 again; the Knight has to move and this allows White's King to defend the f2 Pawn.
How often in Chess is a blunder followed by an even bigger one? White will be a piece to two Pawns up. Sacrificing the Knight does not allow Black to get perpetual check.
Committing suicide! Had Black's Rook been on f6 his game was still lost. White's scattered Pawns would not have been difficult to defend with an extra piece.

Mate would not have been possible if the Bishop wasn't able to own this diagonal - it wins the game for White without making a check of its own!! A fine example of the Bishop's latent power more typically seen in the Fianccheto Bishop.

Hi everyone!

Here is a razor sharp game against Expert Nyctalop.  Nyctalop has kindly commented on my previous annotations so I thought I would try my luck against him.  I tried to attack but it was rebuffed big time.  The story starts with a Scilian Defense. 1. e4  c5.
4. Nxd4 - fairly standard play so far.

5. Nc3 - it is considered bad play to play Nxc6 as bxc6 allows black to build up a pawn centre.  Mind you I did do this exchange in an OTB friendly against a player with an 1824 rating way back in 1999 and went on to win in spectacular fashion.  Sadly I did not notate that game but it is in my memory - my rating was 1240!  Still I decided not to chance it here and play Nc3 - a developing move which defends the pawn on e4.
6. Ndb5 - I go into the Sveshnikov Variation.  This variation is razor sharp as you will soon see.
9. ...... gxf6 - black could have played Qxf6 preserving his kingside pawn structure.
11. Bd3 - defends e4 with development now I am ready to castle and I do so next move.
14. ...... Bg7 - if Nxd5 then Bxf5.  This bishop will be very strong on that diagonal especially when black plays b4 at a convenient moment.
15. Qh5 - Glenda goes to h5 intending to spearhead a mating attack if black castles short.  The move also piles up on the f5 pawn.
15. ...... e4 - crosses my attack on f5 now Fou Leblanc must retreat.  He chooses c2 hitting out indirectly at h7.
17. ...... Qc8 - very strong putting pressure on c3.
19. ..... b4 - at last black plays that dreaded b4.  I take on e4 - it is the last move before we enter open play.
20. ...... bxa3 - the knight goes but I will get my piece back very soon.
21. exf5 - this move looks strong but black has an answer.
22. ..... Ng6 - defends against all threats.  I now decided to regain my piece.  Maybe I should have traded rooks but I leave it to you the Inquest Jury to decide!
24. ...... axb2 - that pawn is gonna be a thorn from now on in.
25. Qf3 - in retrospect maybe Bb3 immediately but then Qxc3.
26. ..... Ne5 - threatening no doubt Nd3.

28. ..... Rc8 - I decided to wave the white flag here as I have no defense to Qc1.  There would follow something like this Variation A

29. h3 Qc1 
30. Qxc1 Rxc1 
31. Rxc1 bxc1=Q+ 

Or just a little bit worse ......

Variation B

29. Qb1 Qc1 
30. Rxc1 Rxc1+ 
31. Qxc1 bxc1=Q+ 
32. Bd1 Qxd1#

Ending up a rook to the bad in Variation A.

So well played there nyctalop.

Part one is done for Tarrasch: his King is secured. Now he needs to get some space for his pieces. The correct move is 8... N-Q2 to be followed up by ...B-B3 and ...N(2)-K4. Tarrasch's KR must guard the KBP against the pressure from White's KB.
A horrendous error in judgement severely weakening Tarrasch's K-side. White promptly takes advantage.
